#. Tag: title
#: security_ad_support.xml:130
#, no-c-format
msgid "Background information for Linux &ad; support"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:132
#, no-c-format
msgid "Many system components need to interact flawlessly to integrate a Linux client into an existing Windows &ad; domain. The following sections focus on the underlying processes of the key events in &ad; server and client interaction."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:139
#, no-c-format
msgid "To communicate with the directory service, the client needs to share at least two protocols with the server:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:146
#, no-c-format
msgid "LDAP"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:148
#, no-c-format
msgid "LDAP is a protocol optimized for managing directory information. A Windows domain controller with &ad; can use the LDAP protocol to exchange directory information with the clients. To learn more about LDAP in general, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha-security-ldap\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:158
#, no-c-format
msgid "Kerberos"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:160
#, no-c-format
msgid "Kerberos is a third-party trusted authentication service. All its clients trust Kerberos authorization of another client's identity, enabling kerberized single-sign-on (SSO) solutions. Windows supports a Kerberos implementation, making Kerberos SSO possible even with Linux clients. To learn more about Kerberos in Linux, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha-security-kerberos\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:171
#, no-c-format
msgid "Depending on which &yast; module you use to set up Kerberos authentication, different client components process account and authentication data:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:178
#, no-c-format
msgid "Solutions based on SSSD"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:182
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem class=\"daemon\">sssd</systemitem> daemon is the central part of this solution. It handles all communication with the &ad; server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:189
#, no-c-format
msgid "To gather name service information, <systemitem class=\"daemon\">sssd_nss</systemitem> is used."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:195
#, no-c-format
msgid "To authenticate users, the <systemitem class=\"resource\">pam_sss</systemitem> module for PAM is used. The creation of user homes for the &ad; users on the Linux client is handled by <filename>pam_mkhomedir</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:209
#, no-c-format
msgid "Solution based on Winbind (Samba)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:213
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem class=\"daemon\">winbindd</systemitem> daemon is the central part of this solution. It handles all communication with the &ad; server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:220
#, no-c-format
msgid "To gather name service information, <systemitem class=\"daemon\">nss_winbind</systemitem> is used."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:226
#, no-c-format
msgid "To authenticate users, the <systemitem class=\"resource\">pam_winbind</systemitem> module for PAM is used. The creation of user homes for the &ad; users on the Linux client is handled by <filename>pam_mkhomedir</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:232
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information about PAM, see <xref linkend=\"cha-pam\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:237
#, no-c-format
msgid "<xref linkend=\"fig-ad-schema\"/> highlights the most prominent components of Winbind-based &ad; authentication."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_ad_support.xml:242
#, no-c-format
msgid "Schema of Winbind-based &ad; authentication"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:256
#, no-c-format
msgid "Applications that are PAM-aware, like the login routines and the &gnome; display manager, interact with the PAM and NSS layer to authenticate against the Windows server. Applications supporting Kerberos authentication (such as file managers, Web browsers, or e-mail clients) use the Kerberos credential cache to access user's Kerberos tickets, making them part of the SSO framework."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_ad_support.xml:266
#, no-c-format
msgid "Domain join"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:267
#, no-c-format
msgid "During domain join, the server and the client establish a secure relation. On the client, the following tasks need to be performed to join the existing LDAP and Kerberos SSO environment provided by the Windows domain controller. The entire join process is handled by the &yast; Domain Membership module, which can be run during installation or in the installed system:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:277
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Windows domain controller providing both LDAP and KDC (Key Distribution Center) services is located."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:283
#, no-c-format
msgid "A machine account for the joining client is created in the directory service."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:289
#, no-c-format
msgid "An initial ticket granting ticket (TGT) is obtained for the client and stored in its local Kerberos credential cache. The client needs this TGT to get further tickets allowing it to contact other services, like contacting the directory server for LDAP queries."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:297
#, no-c-format
msgid "NSS and PAM configurations are adjusted to enable the client to authenticate against the domain controller."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:303
#, no-c-format
msgid "During client boot, the winbind daemon is started and retrieves the initial Kerberos ticket for the machine account. winbindd automatically refreshes the machine's ticket to keep it valid. To keep track of the current account policies, winbindd periodically queries the domain controller."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_ad_support.xml:313
#, no-c-format
msgid "Domain login and user homes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:314
#, no-c-format
msgid "The login manager of &gnome; (GDM) has been extended to allow the handling of &ad; domain login. Users can choose to log in to the primary domain the machine has joined or to one of the trusted domains with which the domain controller of the primary domain has established a trust relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:321
#, no-c-format
msgid "User authentication is mediated by several PAM modules as described in <xref linkend=\"sec-security-ad-background\"/> . If there are errors, the error codes are translated into user-readable error messages that PAM gives at login through any of the supported methods (GDM, console, and SSH):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:330
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Password has expired</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:333
#, no-c-format
msgid "The user sees a message stating that the password has expired and needs to be changed. The system prompts for a new password and informs the user if the new password does not comply with corporate password policies (for example the password is too short, too simple, or already in the history). If a user's password change fails, the reason is shown and a new password prompt is given."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:344
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Account disabled</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:347
#, no-c-format
msgid "The user sees an error message stating that the account has been disabled and to contact the system administrator."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:354
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Account locked out</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:357
#, no-c-format
msgid "The user sees an error message stating that the account has been locked and to contact the system administrator."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:364
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Password has to be changed</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:367
#, no-c-format
msgid "The user can log in but receives a warning that the password needs to be changed soon. This warning is sent three days before that password expires. After expiration, the user cannot log in."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:375
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Invalid workstation</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:378
#, no-c-format
msgid "When a user is restricted to specific workstations and the current &productname; machine is not among them, a message appears that this user cannot log in from this workstation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:386
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Invalid logon hours</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:389
#, no-c-format
msgid "When a user is only allowed to log in during working hours and tries to log in outside working hours, a message informs the user that logging in is not possible at that time."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_ad_support.xml:397
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Account expired</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:400
#, no-c-format
msgid "An administrator can set an expiration time for a specific user account. If that user tries to log in after expiration, the user gets a message that the account has expired and cannot be used to log in."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:408
#, no-c-format
msgid "During a successful authentication, the client acquires a ticket granting ticket (TGT) from the Kerberos server of &ad; and stores it in the user's credential cache. It also renews the TGT in the background, requiring no user interaction."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:414
#, no-c-format
msgid "&productname; supports local home directories for &ad; users. If configured through &yast; as described in <xref linkend=\"sec-security-ad-config\"/> , user home directories are created when a Windows/&ad; user first logs in to the Linux client. These home directories look and feel identical to standard Linux user home directories and work independently of the &ad; Domain Controller."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:422
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using a local user home, it is possible to access a user's data on this machine (even when the &ad; server is disconnected) as long as the Linux client has been configured to perform offline authentication."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_ad_support.xml:431
#, no-c-format
msgid "Offline service and policy support"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:432
#, no-c-format
msgid "Users in a corporate environment must have the ability to become roaming users (for example, to switch networks or even work disconnected for some time). To enable users to log in to a disconnected machine, extensive caching was integrated into the winbind daemon. The winbind daemon enforces password policies even in the offline state. It tracks the number of failed login attempts and reacts according to the policies configured in &ad;. Offline support is disabled by default and must be explicitly enabled in the &yast; Domain Membership module."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:443
#, no-c-format
msgid "When the domain controller has become unavailable, the user can still access network resources (other than the &ad; server itself) with valid Kerberos tickets that have been acquired before losing the connection (as in Windows). Password changes cannot be processed unless the domain controller is online. While disconnected from the &ad; server, a user cannot access any data stored on this server. When a workstation has become disconnected from the network entirely and connects to the corporate network again later, &productname; acquires a new Kerberos ticket when the user has locked and unlocked the desktop (for example, using a desktop screen saver)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_ad_support.xml:458
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuring a Linux client for &ad;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_ad_support.xml:460
#, no-c-format
msgid "Before your client can join an &ad; domain, some adjustments must be made to your network setup to ensure the flawless interaction of client and server."
